New LMS Dismissal Procedures:

Due to Covid-19 and social distancing procedures, students from LMS will all dismiss from the gym. Temporary car tags were handed out during registration that are linked to each student. Please present those car tags to staff each day in the dismissal line. Please see the attached map to understand new traffic flow procedures at LMS. The red X indicates a blocked drive in the afternoons only. Feel free to contact the office if you have any questions.

*Early Arrival each morning begins at 6:45am in the LMS Gym. Students are considered late at 8:00.

*Please pay close attention to the way the traffic flows depending on which entrance you use.

Lexington City School Students

All Lexington City School Students (in-school and virtual) will register Monday, August 3 from 8-12 at their prospective schools. You are advised to do ‚Äúpre-registration‚Äù prior to coming or your wait time will be extensive due to social distancing. Those who are pre-registered will simply pick-up
car tags and grade level paperwork.

Ôøº(The online registration process is the same and is required for both in person and virtual school students. If you plan to attend the virtual learning academy, you must email your respective school principal.)Ôøº

Staggered start of school:

Wednesday, August 5 - only students in grades 3 and 8 (in-school and virtual) will attend.
Thursday, August 6 - only students in grades 1, 4, and 7 (in-school and virtual) will attend.
Friday, August 7 - only students in grades 2, 5, and 6 (in-school and virtual ) will attend.

Monday, August 10 - All students (in-school and virtual) will attend.

After-School Daycare will begin Monday, August 10.

PreK and K students will be contacted by their teachers to follow a regular staggered schedule.

Pandemic-Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) Deadline Extended!!

Don‚Äôt forget! The P-EBT application deadline is extended in Tennessee through Monday, July 13. P-EBT provides money to families with children who receive free or reduced-price school meals.

Eligible families, who do not participate in the SNAP (food stamps) or Families First (TANF) programs, must apply before July 13. Families participating in SNAP or Families First do not have to apply to receive P-EBT. The first P-EBT installment was added to existing EBT cards in June.

NOTICE OF INVITATION TO BID

The Lexington City School System is requesting bids for Fresh Produce for the 2020-2021 school year. Due to the COVID-19 adjustments, the bid packets will be available upon request via email. Please contact the Lexington City School Nutrition Department at (731)968-8457 ext. 406 or by email at pagej@caywood.org. If leaving a message, be sure to include a working email address capable of receiving a multi-page bid document. If you request your document by mail, please allow plenty of time for deliveries to be made since there are deadlines for return.

All bids must be received in the Board Office by 3:00pm on Wednesday, July 8, 2020. Bids will be opened at 10:00am on Thursday, July 9, 2020.

The Lexington City Board of Education reserves the right to accept or reject any or all bids.

If you have any questions, please call Jan Page, School Nutrition Director, at (731) 968-8457 ext. 406.

LCSS Parents,

TDOE Announces Second Phase of PBS Partnership for Summer

We are thrilled to announce a second phase of its partnership with statewide PBS stations to help ensure children continue to have access to educational content during the summer.

Starting June 1, all six Tennessee PBS stations will offer high quality educational programming for grades K-3, weekdays from 10 a.m. ‚Äì12 p.m. CST, through June and July through the Summer Learning Series.

The Summer Learning Series will feature PBS LearningMedia programming that has been specifically chosen for a continued focus on early literacy and math, aligned to Tennessee standards. Each of these programs also have teacher, family, and student resources available online.

A Message from Mrs. Jan Page in the Cafeteria:

The LCSS Emergency Feeding Program will be exercising social distancing from now on when coming to pick up meals at CES. We realize this may take a little longer for everyone, but please know that we will be there as long as it takes for people present to receive their meals. We ask that you stand 6 ft. apart while in the line. We ask that only 1 family at a time be at the pick-up table. We appreciate your cooperation. These precautions are for the safety of all involved. We pray for the safety of all our community and are honored to be able to serve you during this stressful time. God Bless!

5-Day Meal Pick-Up is Monday, March 30th from 1:00-3:00 p.m. at Zone 1 (CES Front Lobby Entrance)

post_text:
At this time, neither the Henderson County Health Department nor the Tennessee Department of Education has made recommendations to close schools to contain the spread of the coronavirus or COVID-19.

As such, there are no plans to close Lexington City Schools (or Henderson County Schools) at this time, though the situation is fluid and we will make decisions on school closures as new information emerges.

We will continue to consult daily with the Henderson County Health Department and the Tennessee Department of Education to make decisions that are in the best interest of our students and staff.

Please spread the word!!!

Community Wide Event hosted by LMS & Homeland Security Investigations ‚ÄúiGuardians‚Äù
January 23rd from 6:00-8:00pm at Lexington Middle School

**This presentation is for adults/parents only.**

Project iGuardian is presented by the U.S. Department of Homeland Security, Homeland Security Investigations (HSI). Project iGuardian is an HSI initiative "designed to inform youths, parents, and educators about the risks that children face in the online environment" that also "aims to arm parents with knowledge and resources to help protect their children." HSI, which is the investigative arm of the U.S. Department of Homeland Security, partnered with the National Center for Missing & Exploited Children to create much of the presentation. We also give example scenarios based on our local investigations to help parents, teachers, and other law enforcement better understand how children can become victimized online.

Lexington City School System - January 2020 Substitute Workshop Notice

The Lexington City School System will host a substitute workshop at the Lexington City School Board Office located at 99 Monroe Ave. in Lexington on Tuesday, January 28, 2020 from 3:30 to 5:00 p.m. Anyone interested in being a substitute teacher in the Lexington City School System should make plans to attend this workshop. Requirements for substitute teachers in the Lexington City School System include completion of an application (must be 21 to apply), successful background check (fingerprinting required), completion of on-site orientation sessions and completion of an annual substitute workshop conducted by the Lexington City School System.

We also give example scenarios based on our local investigations to help parents, teachers, and other law enforcement better understand how children can become victimized online.

post_text:
We would like to say a huge THANK YOU to everyone that helped raise money during the CES Penny War. We broke our highest record by over $2,000 since we started this fundraiser several years ago. This year you helped us raise over $4700. This money goes toward our Christmas Toy Drive. Friday's counting alone took 5 people working all day to make our deadline to announce the winners. We had to team lift 3rd grade's jug and cut it open to get everything out!

We would like to say a special thank you to the Firstbank Tellers at the Natchez Trace branch for counting our deposits. They could not believe the size of the growing deposits each day!

Most of all, to our parents on Facebook, Thank You! The spirit of competition was fierce this year. You provided us with much needed comic relief while counting all of the loose change. We decided to post some of our favorites.

This event was a great example of what a community can do when we all work together and we believe Lexington City Schools has the best!

We had to team lift 3rd grade's jug and cut it open to get everything out!

The VFW‚Äôs Patriot‚Äôs Pen essay contest encourages young minds to examine America‚Äôs history, along with their own experiences in modern American society, by drafting a 300- to 400-word essay, expressing their views based on a patriotic theme chosen by the VFW Commander-in-Chief.
